text:
- she [rebekah mercer] loved me. she was like, oh we need more of your type on our side!

your type? - the gays. she loved the gays. so did steve [bannon]. he saw us as early adopters. he figured, if you can get the gays on board, everyone else will follow. it’s why he was so into the whole milo [yiannopoulos] thing.

robert mercer was a pioneer in ai and machine translation. he helped invent algorithmic trading – which replaced hedge fund managers with computer programs – and he listened to wylie’s pitch. it was for a new kind of political message-targeting based on an influential and groundbreaking 2014 paper researched at cambridge’s psychometrics centre, called: - computer-based personality judgments are more accurate than those made by humans. - in politics, the money man is usually the dumbest person in the room. whereas it’s the opposite way around with mercer, says wylie. - he said very little, but he really listened. he wanted to understand the science. and he wanted proof that it worked.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
at a hearing before the senate judiciary committee, christopher wylie described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters. the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like ‘drain the swamp’ or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the ‘deep state’ that weren’t necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement.

jon sharman
the independent

text:
“the world needs to understand the life cycle of a survivor. i still cry uncomfortably at things, i’m still triggered, and that’s just the reality. when the dr. ford testimony happened, people don’t talk enough about what survival looks like. i have to get up every day to decide to survive. there are some days where i say, i can’t do it today.” - @taranajaneen, founder of the #metoo movement at our #powerwomensummit “it’s not about being bold and brave — it’s about resilience. this is what we’re doing — we’re bouncing back, every day.”
📷 @ecarenphoto
creative director @guerin_ad

this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that’s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him “we can take it.” no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it’s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it’s easy to come along for the ride. there’s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they’re both just characters on the television.

that’s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it’s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it’s that we’ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
*warning*  please be advised that the following is an excerpt from an account of sexual abuse. the full text is only listed at the link below the excerpt..
.
.
.
we have become a people pitted one against the other. invisible is the line that divides us, but the chasm is vast and wide – for we cannot speak, we cannot listen, nor imagine bridging the gap between ourselves and the “other” on that side. the struggle of our time is to bridge that gap, and we are none of us immune to it.

we see battles springing up on every corner of the horizon, and among them is one catalyzed by a great rage building in the hearts of the women in this land. one in three of us has suffered rape, assault, abuse or physical violation of some kind. one in three of us has a story to tell of a burden we are bearing. the stories vary, as do the many ways in which we are wounded, and until now they have mostly been stories we keep to ourselves.

until now. .
.

text: einer der gründe warum ich in leipzig kein auto brauche. unser straßenbahnnetz ist auf platz 2 deutschlandweit. manchmal kann ich alle 5 minuten in eine bahn springen um zum ziel zu kommen...das empfinde ich wirklich als luxus. noch fährt auf unserer linie die alte tatra...mag ich voll gern, weil mich das an meine kindheit und die vielen fahrten mit meiner mama erinnert oder meine ersten fahrten alleine zu meiner oma in den anderen stadtteil. luca hingegen...wartet sehnsüchtig auf die ganz neuen bahnen, die sehen aus, wie bei zurück in die zukunft...😌 ich bin gerade ein wenig nostalgisch, weil ich meine eltern und meine schwester endlich morgen - nach über einem jahr - wiedersehe. unfassbar, wie die zeit rennt....#familytime #leipzig #meinheimatgefühl #straßenbahn #tatra #lieblingsleipzig #iphonexs

text:
the one with a danish journey. 
two years ago, i had the extraordinary experience to meet people so talented, honest, truthful and intelligent. they inspired me and made me fight for what is right. 
our life has changed so much since we walked together. and now, it is time to remember the moment when i found the fire that they are, those eyes that make me see myself so different.

text:
« p o e m »
.
.
.
sometimes, it will go by too fast 
and you will struggle to keep up with it 
but don't worry, it won't last long 
and you'll be know how to resist your own emotions 
and take control over what's already yours 
the word will sting, darling, but trust me 
and listen closely-
it's not over yet, 
the path to your life is still right ahead
even if it's dark, just light your fire 
and watch the world burn for you
.
.
// ayesha fatimah
.
.
.

text:
first, there is no one method or formula for determining #reparations.

so much of the #violence we experience is personalized. the violence we experience as individuals is always shared by other people and communities, yet how it affects us is embodied and related to who we are in this earth walk. that's why this method was designed for people like you and #metoo.

second, calculating reparations is always an economic and #spiritual practice.

above all, the spiritual dimension of this method is central, and #survivors must lead each initiative. the point is to foster #healing, not pay for therapy and legal costs, and give people the support we require to #create #solutions for ourselves and our #beloved communities. so, what does healing mean for you as a #survivor of the violence you seek to stop? given your daily life and needs at this time, what do you need to put in place to #learn and #apply the method?

from a purely economic #perspective, what aspects of healing can financial reparations facilitate? this question is the most direct, but it isn't as simple as it sounds. for example, you might desire therapy and know that therapists cost a rate of, say $60-250 an hour in your town. what if no therapist in your local beloved community speaks your mother language of quechua and that's the language in which you sense the world? what is the honest price tag for your therapy sessions if you have to #travel three hours to see a therapist who shares your #cultural, #linguistic, #ancestral perspective?

text:
“it’s not a parent’s job to keep sex sexy for their kids.” 🙌 preach, zach, preach! today’s episode of voices of your village is a special one as i got to share the mic with my favorite human on this planet. my sweet husband and i dove into teaching sexual consent, what we learned from @conniebritton on #fridaynightlights, and what we hope for our future children’s sex lives. needless to say, this may be an episode you listen to sans kiddos in order to build your toolbox for addressing consent.
•
1 in 3 women is sexually assaulted. folks, we have to stop raising humans who are sexually assaulting other humans. this requires intention because doing it the way we’ve always done it doesn’t seem to be solving the problem. trigger warning: we talk about rape and sexual assault in this episode. we talk about @azizansari and why i’m not mad at him. step outside your comfort zone with us so you can be prepared to raise children who will not be perpetrators of sexual assault. thank you for getting uncomfortable. it’s for a good cause.
•⠀
link in bio or search voices of your village wherever you listen to podcasts. zach and i share our histories with getting the sex talk in this episode. when you were a kiddo did anyone talk to you about sex? if so, how old were you?

احتمالاً خيلى از شما دوستان عزيزمون،از ماجراى #تجاوز_به_کودکان_شوشتر مطلع شدین و مثل ما قلبتون به درد اومده...💔 ولى همه ميدونيم كه اين نه اولين بوده و متأسفانه نه آخرين خواهد بود و همه ى اينها بر لزوم آموزش به #كودكان، اطلاع رسانى راجع به اين موضوع و اهميت ويژه مسئله ى "سلامت روان" و مبارزه هر چه جدى تر با پديده پدوفيليا (رابطه جنسى با كودكان) است
به جاى شرمنده شدن،  صحبت نكردن راجع به اين قبيل موضوعات و در خفا نگه داشتن آن و بروز آسيب هاى جدى ِ بعدى براى كودكانمان، شجاعت و خردمون رو به كار بگيريم و به طرز صحيح و اصولى با اين مشكلات روبرو بشيم... خجالت كشيدن و صحبت نكردن، فقط ميتونه بهاى گرانترى براى پرداخت داشته باشه.
بقول سعدى،شاعر گرانمايه مون:
اى كه دستت ميرسد كارى بكن
پيش از آن كز تو نيايد هيچ كار
❤️
ويديو كامل در igtv و كانال تلگرام ايرانيان زيبا
توصیه میکنیم که حتماً ببينين و از دوستان و آشنايان هم درخواست كنين كه طبق اين ويديو به كودكانشون آموزش بدن
همه چى از خودمون شروع ميشه🙌🏼

text:
press release

new york--- kr3t’s,  choreographers host a celebration for their 29th anniversary called “the east side story, peace in the east”

friday november 16th 8pm show
saturday, november 17th 6pm hors d’oeuvres, 8pm show, 10pm after party
at  #aarondavishall 
in the past, life struggles taught us how to be content and grateful for the little we had.  people now have more clothes, digital gadgets and shoes than they did growing up, but they’re still not happy; and never satisfied.
this show looks at what results from compromising family values for material wealth and how it’s destroying our communities.  we will shine light on the #metoo movement, all the violence in the community and dance tribute for junior who was brutally murdered in the bronx, our goal is to send a positive message to everyone through the art of dance.
 in addition we are glad to have our event hosted by jason andors & imagine, who have appeared on hbo’s bad boys of comedy, comedy central’s premium blend, showtime at the apollo and bet’s comic view.  music by legendary re-mix dj ted smooth.
 five kr3t’s established choreographers will be presenting dance numbers. several have performed on world tours with artists such as j-lo, chris brown, rihanna, beyoncé, lady gaga, usher, kelly rowland, missy elliot, as well on tv shows like the grammy's the vma's jimmy fallon and much more.
our goal is to provide an outlet to develop dance and life skills that will enhance their lifestyles long term. 
no matter what the obstacles, our dancers
keep rising to the top

text:
la semaine dernière avec une amie, nous disséquions les conséquences du mouvement #metoo plus d’un an après. d’après elle, ce mouvement n’était qu’un feu de paille. rien n’allait changer mais au moins, la parole s’était libérée et l’inadmissible allait cesser de rester enfoui sous le tapis. 
bah exactement en fait ! pour ma part, je dis toujours que si la honte change (un peu) de camp, c’est déjà ça de pris. 
parce que moi, j’ai pendant très très longtemps eu honte de ce qui m’était arrivé. aujourd’hui, j’ai beaucoup moins honte et ça en soi, c’est énorme. 
je partage cette photo de moi à l’âge de 11/12 ans parce que j’ai l’impression que c’est là que tout a commencé. avec le début de la puberté. la honte est venue tout de suite et s’est poursuivie pendant une bonne partie de ma vie de femme. 
elle ne m’a quittée que récemment. 
#balancetonporc

text: "this country… needs… no thin idealist, no coarse realist, but a man whose eye reads the heavens, while his feet step firmly on the ground, and his hands are strong and dexterous for the use of human implements… a man of universal sympathies, but self-possessed; a man who knows the region of emotion, though he is not its slave; a man to whom this world is no mere spectacle or fleeting shadow, but a great, solemn game, to be played with good heed, for its stakes are of eternal value, yet who, if his play be true, heeds not what he loses by the falsehood of others; a man who hives from the past, yet knows that its honey can but moderately avail him; whose comprehensive eye scans the present, neither infatuated by its golden lures, nor chilled by its many ventures; who possesses prescience, the gift which discerns tomorrow — when there is such a man for #america, the thought which urges her on will be expressed." -margaret fuller

text:
i love the kind of poems
where we don’t speak to each other

there are airport lounges in the scene, 
beach-side restaurants and
birthday parties of mutual friends

but

it’s the hotel elevators
where conversations happen
when we try to go for the buttons
and our fingers touch

it’s the queues for groceries
where we stand behind one another
and accidentally take a step too soon
or one too late

it’s picking the same book
taking the same taxi
or sitting next to each other at the movies, 
our legs tight for the shiver, 
where our worlds coexist 
for a little while

the tension that builds between us in rooms
is the tickle i take to bed at nights

with my eyes closed, my fingers
draw me to depths of dreams
where we can’t stop talking dirty

and i end up not knowing what to feel
for you except that i know exactly
how i don’t want to

so each day i think of a hundred ways
to spark a conversation with you, 
yet each night, end up closing
with a poem where

we don’t speak to each other.
.
.
animesh ganguly.
(@penningdownthemind)
.
.
.

text:
🙏🎨please share & if you wish to support me in this endeavour just follow the link at the bottom. 🎨🙏
the paris painting ‘venus within’. which i am currently raising funds to help cover costs for participation in the 157th edition of the snba, it will be held in annex of the louvre in paris, france, taking place from 13 to 16 of december 2018. funds will be used for a variety of needs; shipping and travel fees of the artwork and for the artist to travel to the show.
the funds raised will also contribute to a whole series called ‘indestructible women’, it will be displayed here in canada later in 2019 and is what i have always wanted my art and purpose to be about. to show women and the world, that their stories of ‘indestructible women’ hold a place in history. permanently told through paint. for they are truly worthy of having their story inspire others. *please support and share*
i can do it with your help, but i can't do it alone. raising funds to be able to go with my painting to paris and to allow my other series to travel and be seen here in canada, and to especially bring it to the east coast, my home of both newfoundland and labrador. 'from labrador to paris and beyond.' go to:
https://dm2.gofund.me/from-labrador-to-paris-and-beyond

you might think i am crazy 😜 
well i am a little crazy 😝 
i decided to start my 80 day program again this morning... what? why? how?
.
you may ask,how on earth do you think you will have time to do this? .
why would you start a commitment like that a week before thanksgiving 🦃  and during christmas 🎄?
.
well...there is never a good time to start. i want to workout during this time of year. this makes it easy because i have a daily plan. a check list to stick to. .
maybe i make one less batch of cookies, maybe i use gift bags instead of wrapping paper, maybe my house won’t be perfect 👌 that is ok i will be happier if i take care of myself!! .
it is never a good time to start new plan but that is life and if you can be successful when life is crazy you will be wicked successful all the time!!!
.
.

text:
as i look at this candid capture taken during filming on monday, i wonder what i could’ve possibly been thinking...and i’m pretty sure i was having a conversation with myself that went something like this: “wow leah, you made it! i mean, you really really made it! just a few years ago you were living in a 200 square foot room, with every ounce of what you owned tucked into the trunk of your car. you were living in fear, fleeing and hiding from a sadistic abuser who refused to let you go. constantly watching over your shoulder, afraid to walk outside alone, looking around every corner, wondering what may happen next, jumping at every loud noise late at night, praying that the stalking would stop. praying that she’d stop trying to break in. praying that i wouldn’t suddenly disappear and become a news statistic. that was your rock bottom...you lost everything, you cried yourself to sleep every night, in a constant state of fear-induced survival. but look at you now! did you ever in a million years think that this is where you’d be? safe, healed, stronger and happier than you’ve ever been? no, you didn’t expect this, but guess what? this is real. this is your life. this is your truth. you glow girl.” what a difference time makes.
what a difference healing makes.
what a difference survival makes.
what a difference resilience makes!
❤️ #yougogirl
#youglowgirl 
#ifought
#iovercame
#isurvived
#imasurvivor
#metoo 
#dvsurvivor 
#resilience 
#strength
#growth 
#liveresiliently

text:
producer plug:  this three day event is a gift from playwright alyson mead, who in the wake of conversations about consent, sexual assualt and rape has graciously given special permission to perform her timely play "the flora and fauna" across the nation. 
omaha was given permission to perform this show three times, in hopes to reach the wider community. 
all tickets have a $10 suggested donation and all proceeds go to benefit the #metoo movement as we work tirelessly to end sexual assault and rape culture. get tickets at the link here: 
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/the-flora-and-the-fauna-tickets-52185287600

this event features 18 of omaha's finest actors, and we could've cast it 3 times over with the overwhelming support and love we've received from local talent.

reserve your tickets now. share the event. carpool. bring your mothers, husbands, sisters and sons to watch brilliant performances of this searing and honest play. 
the flora and fauna by alyson mead
directed by amy lane and beth thompson
produced by beaufield berry-fisher
with special thanks to steven williams, valerie st. pierre smith and carol danigle.

text:
canção do bandido | ópera
teatro da trindade | 8 a 18 de novembro
qua 19h | qui e sáb 21h | dom 16h30

música & direcção musical nuno côrte-real
libreto pedro mexia
encenação ricardo neves-neves

cantores andré henriques, bárbara barradas, cátia moreso, inês simões, marco alves dos santos e sónia alcobaça
coro do teatro nacional de são carlos e orquestra sinfónica portuguesa

cenário henrique ralheta
figurinos rafaela mapril 
desenho de luz luís duarte 
assistência de encenação rafael gomes e diana vaz

produção executiva força de produção
coprodução teatro da trindade inatel, teatro nacional de são carlos e temporada darcos

partindo do conto tradicional o macaco de rabo cortado, canção do bandido imagina uma personagem que não é um macaco mas um advogado, casanova dos tempos modernos, homem que acumula conquistas e as vai trocando por novas conquistas, sem pensar muito nas consequências dos seus atos. 
o casanovismo e o donjuanismo são revisitados numa época em que as guerras dos sexos (ou dos géneros) já não são o que eram, ou têm pelo menos discursos e legitimidades diferentes. coros gregos e essencialismos em tempos digitais e de #metoo? em quem devemos acreditar: no libreto, nos protagonistas, nos antagonistas, ou nas personagens que, falando em vez de cantar, contestam estes diálogos, estes tipos, esta dialética? 
de d. giovanni à música pop, dos bordões linguísticos aos jogos nonsense, as personagens de «canção do bandido» trazem para o palco tudo o que lhes ocorre, tudo o que sirva as suas estratégias ou ilustra as suas dúvidas. e os espectadores, certamente, tomam partido.

classificação etária | m12

bilheteira

tel: 213 420 000 
e-mail: bilheteira.trindade@inatel.pt

horário da bilheteira
terça a sábado: 14:00 às 20:00
domingo: 14:00 às 18:00
dias de espetáculo até 30 minutos após o início
segunda: encerrada

https://teatrodatrindade-inatel.bol.pt

tomorrow is #whiteribbonday in greater cleveland! the white ribbon campaign offers men, boys, and people of any gender identity an opportunity to speak out against violence and publicly promote healthy relationships.
.
to participate, you can 1. attend the public rally tomorrow at noon on the steps of the cuyahoga county domestic relations courthouse. 2. wear a white ribbon or tie. 3. talk to youth in your life about the meaning of consent. 4. recruit your friends and family to participate.
.

text:
#esdepolitólogos

#china 🇨🇳 | al menos doce activistas —cinco estudiantes de la universidad de pekín, y otros en shanghái, shenzhen y cantón— fueron detenidos el viernes, según ha denunciado el grupo de solidaridad con los trabajadores de jasic. otros tres jóvenes fueron arrestados el domingo en wuhan, en el centro de china. de los estudiantes recién graduados no se sabe su actual paradero. 
los arrestos parecen formar parte de una campaña contra el activismo de estudiantes que se definen a sí mismos como marxistas y defienden la adhesión a los principios comunistas: un grupo aún pequeño, pero que ha ido creciendo a lo largo de los últimos años.

jasic es una fabricante de maquinaria para soldar en shenzhen (sureste de china) cuyos trabajadores intentan organizarse para reclamar mejores condiciones laborales, con el apoyo de los estudiantes. ya este verano, cerca de cuarenta estudiantes, matriculados en la universidad de pekín y en otros de los centros más renombrados del país, fueron detenidos tras participar en actos de apoyo de los trabajadores de esa empresa. 30 obreros fueron arrestados en julio, tras semanas de protestas contra lo que describían como un “trato de esclavos”. más recientemente, los estudiantes han tratado de protestar contra las condiciones laborales en fábricas que suministran componentes a apple y se han solidarizado con mineros que reclaman compensaciones por enfermedades laborales.

según el grupo de solidaridad, uno de los estudiantes detenidos el viernes, zhang shengye, fue “secuestrado” cuando un grupo de hombres vestidos de negro irrumpió en terreno de la universidad, empezó a golpear al joven y lo metió a rastras en un automóvil. otros testigos afirman que también fueron agredidos. “este es otro de los delitos que las universidades han cometido contra los estudiantes progresistas y la comunidad de izquierdas”, denuncia el grupo.

zhang se había significado en los últimos meses por sus protestas para conseguir la libertad de yue xin, una estudiante líder del movimiento #metoo en los campus chinos y que figura entre los detenidos este verano por apoyar a los trabajadores de #jasic.

text:
blood diamond_maddy bowen (1/2) happy #monologuethursday folks! as the holiday season approaches, i feel like it gets even easier to get detached from the reality of the world around us - you know, everything sparkles and smells of cinnamon and we want to lose ourselves in that magic, beautiful, happy world that doesn't really exist. which is fine, don't get me wrong. but still. being my other job in the fashion industry i see this stuff all the year around, and sometimes i feel the need to bring things back to reality.
wether it's fur, or diamonds, or anything that implies beauty being at the cost of someone else's happiness, freedom, or life, we should take a moment and really look through that beautiful, yet deadly thing. and maybe, ask ourselves if there isn't another way to make the world function. because there must be. 
love,
#agirlfromtheislandinnewyork

text:
lately (lol the past 3 yrs) i’ve been doubting whether i did the right thing choosing film school over business school. like i’ve always been into film and wanting to work in the film industry and coming out of high school the last thing i wanted was to do three years of econometrics, statistics and fiscal policies. but now nearing the end of my degree in film i feel like maybe i should’ve suffered thru that and having kept my passion for film as a hobby. then i realized damn there’re probably so many people out there studying business & economics with an interest in film but the number of people studying film interested in business & economics are definitely a lot fewer. and what i love about studying film and having business & economics as like a “hobby interest” is that i get to have a passion about something that a lot of people think are boring and odd to have a passion for as an art student. i guess what i’m saying is maybe i would’ve regretted it too if i chose an economics degree 3 yrs ago, and that there’ll always be several pathways to reach your goals and none of them are gonna be right or wrong. don’t you think? 
did a lil youtube video on the topic, check it out! link in bio. ❤️

text:
#throwbackthursday to this time last year. i was desperately unhappy and in a cycle of self-destructive behaviour that not only affected me and my wellbeing, but that of others as well. i did a lot of things in 2017 i’m not proud of and i honestly believed for a long time that nothing would ever get better, that i wouldn’t make it to 30 because everything was too much. in january of this year, i attempted to end my life, and was later sexually assaulted by a stranger. my family was falling apart around me and my life just felt like it was spiralling out of my control, no matter how hard i fought. i’m not saying everything is perfect now - i don’t like my appearance and have ongoing familial issues - but i’ve just accepted a job in a place that makes me feel genuinely happy for the first time in my life. i don’t feel powerless to the demons in my head or the whims of others anymore. i am my own woman, the woman i thought i’d lost. there’s still a long way to go, but i’ve taken some very serious steps towards being the person i want to be. and i’m proud of myself for that. .
.
.
.
.
#november #2018 #winter #transformation #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth #beforeandafter #mentalhealthjourney #thursdaymotivation #thursday #bosslady #reasonstolive #motivation #metoo

i don't normally use my buisness as a platform to get political. however today i am. 
the beautiful women pictured here is my husbands aunt. she was brutally and coldly murdered by her husband in 2001 who was sentance to life in prison in 2002 for first degree murder. i never had the chance to meet aunt shelley but ever since i started dating my husband 12 years ago i have felt her presence in the family. she was the laughter and light of his family. she still is today even though shes not with us.

my mother in law recently did some digging into the status of aunt shelley's murderer and found out he was in a minimum security prison that is dorm style. he has monthly escorted leaves from prison...and is married with a daughter! he was charge with first degree murder becuase he planned out her murder for days and ended her life in a stomach turning and horrific manner. he should be in maximum security prison with no access to the public for everyones safety. our family had no idea about this information until one month ago and we are outraged. 
we are going public with this information in the hope to change the correction system in canada and to plead with the public that if you had a loved one murdered to check on their killers status in prison. because the punishment should fit the crime. honestly canada...if this evil man didn't remain in a maximum security prison, what do you have to do to remain there?

in the link.tree link in my bio you will find a link to the cbc article that explains everything in even more depth. however i warn you the article is graphic and heart breaking. but its a story that needs to be told so hopefully change can happen. i pray some of my 560 instagram and 180 facebook followers will read the article and help our family spread the word about this injustice. 
thank you for reading this caption. there is so much more i could say but the cbc article truely says it all. ♡ kaitlyn *
*
*

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
2018 환경재단 후원의밤 
서지현검사님이 상을 받으셨다.
"어둠을 물리치는 방법은 어둠 속에서 몸부림치는 것이 아니라 촛불 하나를 켜는 것"
"내가 몸부림칠 때 그 어떤 빛도 보이지 않았다. 결국 스스로 작은 촛불 하나 켜려고 했는데 그것이 온몸을 불살라야 하는 것임을 알게 됐다"
"그렇게 환하게 뜨거웠다가 지려 하오, 불꽃으로. 검찰은, 강자는 두려우나 나는 그리 선택했소."

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most impoant, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
one year later *** dear benjamin brenner gerard (the one who sexually assaulted me),
i forgive you. you do not deserve to be held in my thoughts. you do not deserve to remain immortal in my fears. i forgive you for being weak. i forgive you for being the person you are, the child you will never grow out of, and the delusions you hold. i will never stop defending myself, however i will stop allowing you to have any remaining power over me. i forgive you for allowing your parents to hire a horrible lawyer to protect their 26 year old child. i forgive you for having faults that leads you to needing to force yourself upon others. i forgive you for being so weak and insecure that sexual assault is the way you pretend to have power. i forgive you. thank you for creating a situation in which i learned how strong and intelligent i truly am.

penned from my self worth,
sophie stephen **
#uwm #uwmilwaukee #metoo #mytruth #timesup #tw #survivorpride #sexualassault #ripthemaskoffrapists #silence

text:
today parents, advocates and caregivers go to the massachusetts state house to make nicky’s law a reality.
.
our children/adult children are vulnerable to physical and sexual abuse. abuse cases are very difficult to prosecute and when the victim is unable to speak/testify well it is nearly impossible.

the boston globe highlighted to the 30% rise in abuse to this population. 
parents and advocates want their children to be safe and need to prevent abusers from returning to a job with this vulnerable population.
.
.
.
please learn about nicky’s law and consider mobilization to create a law in your state. this is a national issue and we must all act now!
.
.
.
.
.

text:
mới đây, ceo thương hiệu nội y đình đám victoria’s secret - jan singer vừa đệ đơn từ chức sau hàng loạt chỉ trích trước phát ngôn thiếu tế nhị của ed razek - giám đốc phụ trách marketing của hãng về người mẫu chuyển giới. 
cụ thể trong một bài phỏng vấn với tạp chí vogue, ed razek cho rằng ông không nghĩ người mẫu chuyển giới sẽ sải bước trên sàn diễn thương hiệu victoria’s secret bởi vì đó (buổi trình diễn) là “một giấc mơ”, “chương trình giải trí đặc biệt kéo dài 42 phút”, “chúng tôi (victoria’s secret) là tình yêu đầu của họ. và victoria’s secret vẫn luôn là tình yêu đầu của phụ nữ ngay từ đầu”. ed razek có lập luận riêng của mình khi đưa ra câu trả lời trên. tuy nhiên, phong trào #metoo cùng những hiệu ứng xung quanh đã khiến câu nói của vị giám đốc này thu hút làn sóng chỉ trích gay gắt từ cư dân mạng. trang thông tin chính thức của vs sau đó cũng đã đăng tải lời xin lỗi của ed razek, nhưng có lẽ lời xin lỗi đó chưa thể hoàn toàn xoa dịu cộng đồng mạng xã hội ngay lúc này.

cụ thể trong một bài phỏng vấn với tạp chí vogue, ed razek cho rằng ông không nghĩ người mẫu chuyển giới sẽ sải bước trên sàn diễn thương hiệu victoria’s secret bởi vì đó (buổi trình diễn) là “một giấc mơ”, “chương trình giải trí đặc biệt kéo dài 42 phút”, “chúng tôi (victoria’s secret) là tình yêu đầu của họ. và victoria’s secret vẫn luôn là tình yêu đầu của phụ nữ ngay từ đầu”. ed razek có lập luận riêng của mình khi đưa ra câu trả lời trên. tuy nhiên, phong trào  cùng những hiệu ứng xung quanh đã khiến câu nói của vị giám đốc này thu hút làn sóng chỉ trích gay gắt từ cư dân mạng. trang thông tin chính thức của vs sau đó cũng đã đăng tải lời xin lỗi của ed razek, nhưng có lẽ lời xin lỗi đó chưa thể hoàn toàn xoa dịu cộng đồng mạng xã hội ngay lúc này.

text: in aa i have been told to “turn it over” every day i walk into the rooms or speak to a loving sponsor. i can say that humility has served me so well when it comes to my recovery and has allowed me my greatest asset!  to be vulnerable and never drink or drug!  my ego wants me to hide my true spirit, wants me to believe i can handle my drinking, i can quit after the next line or hit or whatever....the ego knows no love, only how to crave.  my ego brought me to these rooms at a young age because “i did it my way” stepping on everyone including myself.  i was broken because i had a false sense of ego driving my life that was insatiable.  i had no concept of god as i came to know him on my terms, he was never there to save me as a kid from all my trauma. i never stopped running long enough to consider that you guys were having these meetings and all i had to do was show up!  i stayed out of a longing robe loved and understood and quit using because my “life had become unmanageable” at 26 years old.  what i ended up learning was that i could face my entire lifetime of childhood trauma, mental illness, addiction in every area of my life and find a life of love, purpose and willingness to help others.  i still have to do the basics everyday, i check my ego at the door, pull up a chair and at the end of the day “my name is laura, i am an alcoholic and an addict, i am so glad you are here”  i love you, i really do because i have truly learned what unconditional love is.  #metooneveryou #theshamelesswarrior #aa #billw #alcoholicsanonymous #sobrietyismylove #sober #sobriety #sobrietyquotes #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #mentalillness #traumahealing #bipolar #add #adhd #autismawareness #autism #recoveryispossible #recoveryisworthit #violenceagainstwomen #metoo #timesup
name: Laura Goodman

text:
i don’t preach, i pretty much keep my political opinions to myself.  i’m not the rock the boat type. you are entitled to your opinion, i am entitled to mine, i don’t have to agree with yours and you don’t have to agree with mine. 
but, #metoo is a valuable lesson everyone needs to learn from. everyone, not only women, should be able to come forward about something that’s happened to them without fear of retaliation.  nys has entered the movement requiring that all employees take part in a sexual harassment course.  everyone. that’s how important this is. 
the unfortunate lack of regulation so far basically let’s anyone give this course as long as you meet the state’s criteria. the seminar i attended last night, i was appalled. (not set up by myself and i will give the benefit of the doubt that the individuals who set it up were unaware)

if your first anecdote on the #sexualharassment course you are giving is that “i was accused and i beat it”, we should have just stopped there. you are the epitome of why this movement was so important.  the rest of the presentation was appalling and the lack of care taken to put it together was beyond disappointing.  your job was to empower the attendees to have a voice, but you decided to spout your sad little story and shoot down the very event you’re supposed to provide power to.

i hope people know that this one person does not represent the people who really do care about your safety and your ability to come forward and be heard and believed. i will always be a welcoming place to come should you need the shoulder to cry on or the shoulders to lift you up and empower the strength i know you have.

#shareyourstory #dontbeafraid #standstrong #empowerpeople #empowerwomen #bestrong

text:
we are entering the second edition of 16 film festival in conjunction with #16daysofactivism in the global movement to fight gender based violence. 
we hope to elevate the consciousness level and the courage through our 16 feature and 16 short films in our line up this year.
film adalah media yang ampuh untuk menggambarkan kejadian kejadian dalam masyarakat kita yang kerap bersentuhan dengan kekerasan berbasis gender dan seksualitas. lewat film kita melihat, mendengar, menumbuhkan rasa empati yang tak jarang berujung pada tumbuhnya kekuatan kolektif untuk mencari solusi dan memberantas kekerasan berbasis gender & seksualitas ini.

16 film festival terus berupaya membangun ruang ruang aman untuk berdidkusi, berekspresi, mencurahkan isi hati dan menciptakan support group yang memperkuat kesadaran kemanusiaan. 
meningkatnya angka kekerasan di negri ini memang memprihatinkan. tapi, bukan hal yang tidak mungkin, bahwa kenaikan angka tersebut diakibatkan kesadaran dan keberanian yang tumbuh sehingga setiap kasus meningkatkan kepedulian bersama.

saat ini keberpihakan pada korban lah yang harus diperjuangkan pada aparat dan institusi institusi formil. ruang 16 film festival pun terbuka bagi mereka-mereka yg duduk pada posisi krusial penegakan hukum negri ini.

ayo beranjak, dan turut hadir di 16 film festival! mulai tgl 25 mov -10 desember. besok kita akan jumpa pers dulu di @soulfood.id follow @enambelasffest untuk updatenya. #16filmfestival #zerotolerance #domesticviolence #genderviolence #hearmetoo #metoo #humanrights #womensright #activism #filmfestival #indonesia #komnasperempuan #16haktp #unaids #asv #viuindonesia

then why does the irish government think underwear is a consent to be raped? how does a 27 year old man get found not guilty of raping a 17 year old girl, simply because “look at what she was wearing, a thong with a lacy front”. these are not words used in the paper to draw attention to readers, these are not words whispered between elderly ladies who watched her pass by, these are not friends judging her as she gets changed; no, these are worse spoken by an actual lawyer. a person with a degree, a person believed to know right from wrong, to know consent vs the word no. the irish government has not only let down this poor girl, but they have left down any woman who feels empowered in her own body, who feels she can wear whatever underwear she wants without a man thinking he has a right to touch her without asking. the world is growing and changing, women are no longer afraid to sexualise their own bodies, or to then make their bodies un-sexualised. why is me posting this considered more shameful than a man to do the same? nobody has ever asked a rapist what they were wearing, have they? why?; because what you wear isn’t inviting a crime. “the truth of it is, the shame was not mine, and for all victims in similar situations, it is not ours. the shame is reserved for every creep who has ever touched us inappropriately. the shame is on the abuser, not the victim, not the survivor. it is tragic that so many of us have to survive this kind of crap, and i’m so sorry if it has happened to you” - rose mcgowan. 🥀#thisisnotconsent #clothingdoesnotequalconsent #nomeansno #metoo #metoomovement #metoo #rosemcgowan

text:
be intentional....
with the holidays upon us, we will begin preparing for family gatherings and making sure we have all the right ingredients for a great meal. but, before you get too caught up in grocery shopping, pie baking, and table setting, be sure to start a dialogue with your child. take this opportunity to ask them how they feel about the various friends and family members they will likely be seeing at the upcoming family gathering and really listen to what they say about each individual. reiterate the concepts of boundaries and body autonomy. reassure them that they can come to you at anytime about anyone who makes them feel uncomfortable or touches them in any way that they don't like and you will listen to them and make it stop. being intentional in these discussions can help your child feel more comfortable telling you hard truths about the people you know and love without fear of not being heard or believed.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
"the idea for this book came to me as i was about to publish women’s anthology uncaged: the rise of the badass post #metoo. i was thinking about my then three-year-old son and wondering about the type of man he would grow up to be. i thought about my six-year-old daughter, contemplating how effective it would be raising a girl with a voice and clear boundaries if these couldn’t protect her from the actions of those around her.

growing up i felt more connected to boys and men than i did girls and women; misogyny lives within us all, women too. yet i couldn’t help observing the extent to which boys are also the victim of a deeply wounded, abusive culture."

text:
📍 место дня: @momuziejus в вильнюсе
⠀
совсем недавно в вильнюсе появился новый музей современного искусства – mo muziejus. мы уже успели съездить на разведку в этот значимый хайлайт литовской столицы.
⠀
⠀
на площади более 3000 кв. метров собрали около 5000 работ местных художников, и теперь это самый крупный частный музей в стране.
⠀
изучение коллекции стоит начинать с третьего этажа: там четыре просторных зала, которые прямо сейчас занимает выставка «all art is about us». на ней собраны работы литовских художников, созданные в период с начала 50-х гг. до наших дней. произведения рассказывают о прошлом и настоящем страны, города и людей в нем, транслируют общую боль и радость и впечатляют размашистой палитрой техник. обрати внимание на «героев» кисти mikalojus šalkauskas – у картины занимательный жизненный цикл и множество незаметных деталей – и гиперреалистичный проект «влияние»  братьев gataveckai – у него сильный социальный подтекст. и обязательно отыщи полотна местного (а точнее, местной) пикассо.
⠀
затем спускайся на этаж ниже – там найдешь трогательную подборку фоторабот о повседневности литовской сср – что-то очень нам понятное.
⠀
🎧  для более вдумчивого погружения в контекст советуем не игнорировать онлайн-аудиогид (он доступен на английском): узнаешь истории создания работ, их скрытые смыслы, кто из художников оказался замешан в #metoo и что музей думает по этому поводу. выводы можно сделать самостоятельно.
⠀
кроме того, в мо есть библиотека и приятный сувенирный магазин, кафе, пространство для мероприятий  и огромное хранилище. к слову, оно не спрятано под семью замками, а находится прямо на первом этаже здания за стеклянной стеной к радости всех любопытных глаз.
⠀
⠀
▪ адрес:  pylimo g. 17, vilnius
⠀
📸  @murmurash
⠀
#34travel

text: anxiety is rooted in inadequacy and insecurity. almost everything i overthink is about my failing or coming up short in some way, shape, or form: not being fast enough at work, not being efficient enough in my daily life, not being eloquent enough in conversation, not being smart enough for a seat at this table, not being talented enough to express and execute this project the way i need and want to. etc. it’s that little word “enough.” it’s almost always followed by doubt, doubt, and more doubt. it saps my energy. so today i’m not going to follow it up with anything. right now i’m not going to overthink beyond it. i am enough. period. ✨ #iamenough #anxiety #cptsd #mentalhealthawareness #workinprogress #survivor #survivorselfcare #selfcare #believesurvivors #believeblackwomen #metoo

text:
clothing is not consent 
why is it that the victim is always blamed ? i just don't get it. nobody asks to be raped, not by what they wear, who they hang around with or where they go. it's not the victims fault. our justice system is a sham for rape victims, humiliated in court and asked to show up underwear suggesting it may have given consent. underwear is evidence, evidence of the rape culture that exists in ireland. in ireland 42% of women have experienced sexual abuse, but only 10% was reported and only 8% of trials result in convictions. we need to come together, and try to change things 
i'm sure most of you have seen posts in the media recently surrounding rape and certain cases that have come up. if anyone's finding it difficult to deal with i can assure you you're not alone. my page is always open to anyone, sometimes a listening ear can do the world of good

text:
hello all, this year itm group of institutions will be celebrating international men's day on november 19, 2018 (monday). most people don't even know that there is, in fact, an internationally recognized day for men... and most people laugh at the idea of celebrating it. "isn't every day men's day?" is the common refrain.

we think that men should be acknowledged, recognized and celebrated... not just for their achievements and conquests, but for the roles they play in our society.

our theme this year is:
"hero ka hero"
- celebrating positive male role models

especially in light of the wave of #metoo allegations, and the spotlight that's been aimed at male behaviour, we must take the time to acknowledge that there are men who have been raised well, who treat everyone as equals and make us proud through how they live their lives.

so let's "remember the names of our fathers" and cherish the relationships we have with the men in our lives and our communities and celebrate international men's day!

#itmmovember 
#internationalmensday 
#comingsoon
#mensday 
#menshealthmatters 
#menmatter 
#men

cork, irlanda, ottobre 2018.
un ragazzo 27enne, accusato di stupro nei confronti di una ragazza di 17 anni, è stato assolto in quanto lei indossava un tanga di pizzo quella sera. la legale dell'uomo durante l'arringa di difesa ha portato l'intimo della ragazza come prova che lei quella sera fosse disposta ad avere rapporti sessuali. non so se mi fa più schifo il fatto che la prova sia stata accettata in tribunale o che l'avvocato in questione è una donna. io mi chiedo, mia cara elisabeth o'connell, un perizoma in vita tua non lo hai mai messo? e se lo hai fatto era perché quei giorni eri disposta ad avere rapporti sessuali con chiunque incontrassi? medioevo ben tornato tra di noi.
.
.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
beyoncé hat ihre partnerschaft mit dem britischen tycoon und topshop-besitzer sir philip green beendet, nachdem dieser sich mit vorwürfen zu sexuellem missbrauch und rassistischen äußerungen konfrontiert sah. sie erwarb nun seinen anteil von 50 prozent und übernimmt damit die volle kontrolle über das sport-label ivy park, das sie gemeinsam mit green 2016 gegründet hatte. 
ivy park gab die bedingungen des deals nicht bekannt.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
14-nov-2018:  seminar on 'women of marginalised communities: concerns about exclusion' held in amu

aligarh, #november 14: #women have rights equal to that of men, but they continue to face disparity with unequal treatments and perceptions wholly or partly due to their gender, said prof zakia athar siddiqui, former director, advanced centre for women's studies, aligarh muslim university (amu), while delivering the keynote address in the indian council of social science research (icssr) sponsored national seminar on 'women of marginalised communities: concerns about exclusion' at the #arts faculty lounge.

in the seminar organised by the advanced centre for women's studies, prof zakia pointed out that we need to focus on how to help women to overcome vulnerabilities and shape their destinies in the national #growth story. "to help women of marginalised communities, we need to understand that equality for women is progress for all," she said adding that gender equality, women empowerment, women rights and the eradication of poverty are essential to economic and social development.

mr nizam pasha, advocate, supreme court of india said that women, across castes and classes, are marginalised, even if the degree varies. speaking on the #metoo movement, he pointed out that the campaign needs to have representations from dalit, bahujan, adivasi and other marginalised women. "let us build more resources and support for the most vulnerable and marginalised as any campaign should not treat the most vulnerable as just an afterthought," he said.

mr pasha also spoke on better enforcement of sexual harassment laws and setting up of tribunals for women in the informal sector.

quoting swami vivekananda, prof akbar husain, dean, faculty of social sciences said, "there is no chance of the welfare of the world unless the condition of women is improved." he pointed out, "women are all powerful if they have strong mind, confidence in their body language and maturity in handling relationships. empowerment is an internal attribute. a woman may feel empowered if she is contended with herself in physical, emotional, mental, social and spiritual terms."

text: ett av mina absolut största problem är min medkänsla. jag jobbar stenhårt på att inte låta den korrumpera mig, jag måste aktivt bestämma mig för att inte förlåta bara för att jag förstår eller känner med någon. ”everyone is fighting a battle you know nothing about. be kind. always.” gulligt citat men fucking omöjligt när man behöver freda sig. jag har levt hela mitt liv sådär. tänkt på och försökt sätta mig in i andras bagage och liv och känt medkänsla. till och med mot min förälder som våldtog mig. mot mina hallickar som sålt mig. alla torskar som köpt mig. alla människor som på olika sätt svikit mig. ”everyone is fighting a battle”. problemet är att när man väl vet att ens förälder ju faktiskt också blev slagen och psykiskt misshandlad så är det svårt att lägga skulden på hen. eller när man vet att torsken är änkling och saknar sin fru. det blir svårt när man ska grubbla på och tycka synd om och känna med sina förövare. det blir liksom ”okej, han har den bakgrunden och dessa skälen och smärtpunkter, jag förstår varför han måste våldta mig för att må bättre”. det är destruktivt att leta förklaringar till sina förövares ageranden. ofta leder det till nån sorts acceptans och i värsta fall förlåtelse. jag tränar hela tiden på att skilja mellan förståelse och förlåtelse. jag vet varför min förälder våldtog mig - jag förstår vart hen kommer ifrån. men att förstå något betyder inte att man måste förlåta. jag hatar sån där ”välj lycka” propaganda om att man inte ska va arg eller att man ska släppa taget om sin ilska. ilska är en känsla som är till för att sätta gränser. om jag ger upp ilskan, ger jag upp mina gränser. ilska är den absolut viktigaste känslan jag har. jag har alldeles för mycket kärlek för mitt eget bästa. men man kan inte ge den till sina våldtäktsmän. förstå, men inte förlåta. älska rätt personer och hata dom som gjort sig värda det. att känna med alla och förstå och förlåta allas beteenden är orimligt. men jag har levt nästan hela mitt liv så. trängt bort ilskan och letat svar och förklaringar. det finns inga ursäkter. ett övergrepp är ett övergrepp är ett övergrepp. #metoo #prostitution #utanskyddsnät #intedinhora

text:
‘i was 8 years old when i met this devil. his face, his voice, this moment outside time have remained for years repressed in a corner of my mind.
the #metoo movement, the awareness of our time and the inspiring collective force of all those who've spoken up, have awakened something in me too.
my own story resurfaced and in response, i wrote. music and lyrics came together, like a monologue of the girl i was, spoken by the woman i am now.
"devil's calling" is a true story, i wrote it to no longer hide it, to heal myself, so that other people like me can know that they are not alone’. link in bio 👆🏼thank u so much to the amazing team who made it possible ! @ogmore03 @smartaleck_paris @noa_yehonatan @cecilpetit @gclorusso @virginieborgeaudbigot @sophie.chessoux @labelwarner @bertrandlamblot #newvideo #devilscalling #video thank u @david_pearl for the design 🙏🏻

text: zur frage, was frauen an klamotten trugen, als "es" passiert ist: dieses kleid trug eine frau, die ich gut kenne, im april 2017, als sie einen jungen mann in einer diskothek kennen lernte, der sie später vergewaltigte. das kleid hat lange ärmel und darunter trug die damals 22jährige dichte thermo-leggins... für sie ist dieses kleid ein erinnerungsstück mit erinnerungen, die man nicht einfach wegwaschen kann. deswegen war es, genau wie die leggins, seit der tat auch noch nie in der waschmaschine. es braucht wahrscheinlich noch zeit, bis es dort oder auf dem müll landet. oder wieder auf einer tanzfläche... das weiß die frau, die ich gut kenne und die seitdem noch nie wieder tanzen war, noch nicht... ebenso, wie sie nicht weiß, was sie mit dem kleid tun soll, weiß sie auch sonst nicht, wie sie mit ihren erinnerungen bezüglich dieser nacht umgehen soll... denkt ihr, ihr kleid hatte "schuld" daran, dass der junge mann später so agiert hat? ich glaube das nicht. #thisisnotconsent #metoo #gesellschaft #sexualstrafrecht #neinheißtnein #neinheisstnein #nomeansno #sex #männer #frauen #party #leben #traurig #gesetz #recht #dontrape #ptbs #nachrichten #kleidung #potd #germanblogger #woman #frausein #kleiderfrage

text_retweet:
i had a friend tell me once that it was her feeling that when people talk about what they’ve been through, they do it for attention or are playing the victim. imagine that. such backward thinking. as we grow, we no longer hold onto our “story” or let our circumstances define us, and the stories simply become a way to help others through the pain of being stuck in a belief system that needs to change.*
*
each story is like a level in a video game: you aren’t meant to get stuck on that level. you’re meant to collect the tools you can and move on to the next level, so don’t be afraid to share your stories. they will help someone who is in great pain figure out that what they’re going through is all a part of their growth as souls on this journey, nothing more. *
*
and if you are afraid to share your story because you’re worried about what others will think of you, do some work around forgiving yourself and get to that deep level of understanding that this needs to be set free. we can’t help others until we’ve helped ourselves.*
*
_____
#repost @whywomendontleave

text:
minding the gap (2018)
.
minding the gap is a documentary that’s directed by bing liu. the film is about a
young men that bond together to escape volatile families in their rust-belt hometown. as three they face adult responsibilities, unexpected revelations threaten their decade-long friendship. it stars bing liu himself, kiere johnson, and zack mulligan.
.
this hulu documentary is one of the winners in sundance film festival. it win special jury award for breakthrough filmmaking. so, there’s no reason to not get hype watching the film. after watching the film, i must say that this film is one of the best film of 2018.
.
first of all, this film told bing liu’s and his 2 friend story. so, this film tells a true story. the film is simply magnificent. the film’s story and the realism that’s told by 12 years of footage that greatly combined by bing liu is the driving force in the film. to be honest, i think it’s one of the best documentary i’ve watch.
.
the film’s camera work is beautiful. especially the footage that he made. like the use of fish eye, and the old camera back in the 90’s. it just transcend you to the video store generation. also, one of the example of the camera work that i love is when he shows us 2- 3 minutes of his friends skating through the town. i also want to give credit to the editing, 
and the way the truth unravel from the interview, so we can see the reaction and the emotion they all feel.
.
the problem that the film talk about is truly heart-breaking. abusive home is something that we hear people talk every day. but, to see their side of story, you couldn’t avoid the thought of being lucky not to experience that. the film just make us fell sympathetic.
.
also, criticizing this film is kinda heart because, for me, documentary is like watching someone else’s memory, especially this film. the reason why i think this film is magnificent because i can see myself in one of the person in the film. relating to this film is very easy, and i think that’s the reason why people like this film.
.
grade : 9.3/10
.
as always thank you for reading this review. don't forget to drop a like and comment. #likeforlike

text:
harrassment of any form is wrong. be it physical or emotional. the idea of sex & consent are mutually exclusive. there can’t be sex without consent. because sex without consent, is not sex—it’s rape, and rapes happen not only in work places , even in relationships and marriages.

whether you're speaking out as part of the #metoo movement or holding on to your story, every single person deserves to feel safe, happy and live past the physical/mental trauma they've been part of.

easier said than done, living in a society which keeps reminding us of the past we want to forget. key is to
 heal and understand that the past doesn't defile our honour nor define who we are, and what matters is how we want to live in the present, leading upto the future.

what better way to heal than talk to someone who truly understands and is qualified to help without passing judgements. :) whoever you're, if you have a story to share and heal from, use my code "metoosurya" to avail a free counseling session with an expert on beamitlive from the smile again foundation. 
spread the word! 
code link here - http://bit.ly/metoosurya

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most impoant, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company’s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you’re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person’s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the “training set” refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your “feature set”: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it’s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data – the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you’re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text: you know when you get sucked down the rabbit hole of something that triggers you and you’re straight in there, not so composed, not so articulate but loud, really quite loud? 🙈 ohhhh no... well, ‘out of the blue’ (or the oblivious for those who listen to @abrahamhickspublications ) this conversation popped up about an advert in australian cinemas. basically, the dad is picking teenage son and younger daughter up from school. boy gets in and complains he got detention for flicking up a girls skirt. dad says “what, detention just for that...it’s only a bit of fun” (or words to this effect). the girl sitting in the back of the car then pipes up and says, “yes, as a girl i’ve already accepted that i’m going to be harassed or even abused at times.” the dad takes a moment and says “no, that’s not what i meant.” end of advert. so you get the idea. i thought this was brilliant. subtle but so on point. the conversation went between our group... well the dad didn’t mean it like that, and neither did the son, was just a bit of fun. no no no no and no some more! in this moment i realised i don’t have a sense of humour around this topic, at all. if that makes me uptight then so be it. fun is funny. right? being harassed or abused is not funny, whatever your intention. and as women we have a responsibility to voice that this isn’t fun, funny or acceptable. stop laughing it off girls, if it doesn’t feel good that’s because it isn’t, say so🙏🏻💖 #beheard #speakyourtruth #tellitlikeitis #itsnotok #female #wellbeing #emotionalhealth #mentalhealth #spiritualhealth #selflove #empowered #selfcare #femaleempowerment #divinefeminine #speakup #saywhatsonmymind #heal #womenhelpingwomen #goddess #highvibe #raiseyourvibration #sharing #foodforthought #metoo
